"Pinto J., Bonacic C., Hamilton-West C., Romero J., Lubroth J.","Climate change and animal diseases in South America",2008,"OIE Revue Scientifique et Technique","27","2",,"599","613",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-53349143369&partnerID=40&md5=22e1b287a7ef9b9f045b469555d2b5c3","Emergency Prevention System for Transboundary Animal and Plant Pests and Diseases, Global Early Warning and Response System (EMPRES/GLEWS), Animal Health Service, Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, Viale delle Terme di Caracalla, Rome, 00153, Italy; Fauna Australis, Facultad de Agronomía e Ingeniería Forestal, Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile (PUC); Programa de Doctorado en Ciencias Silvoagropecuarias, Campus Sur, Universidad de Chile; Universidad Peruana Cayetano Heredia, Lima, Peru","Pinto, J., Emergency Prevention System for Transboundary Animal and Plant Pests and Diseases, Global Early Warning and Response System (EMPRES/GLEWS), Animal Health Service, Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, Viale delle Terme di Caracalla, Rome, 00153, Italy; Bonacic, C., Fauna Australis, Facultad de Agronomía e Ingeniería Forestal, Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile (PUC); Hamilton-West, C., Programa de Doctorado en Ciencias Silvoagropecuarias, Campus Sur, Universidad de Chile; Romero, J., Universidad Peruana Cayetano Heredia, Lima, Peru; Lubroth, J., Emergency Prevention System for Transboundary Animal and Plant Pests and Diseases, Global Early Warning and Response System (EMPRES/GLEWS), Animal Health Service, Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, Viale delle Terme di Caracalla, Rome, 00153, Italy","Climate strongly affects agriculture and livestock production and influences animal diseases, vectors and pathogens, and their habitat. Global warming trends predicted in the 2007 Intergovernmental Panel on Climatic Change (IPCC) report for South America are likely to change the temporal and geographical distribution of infectious diseases, including those that are vector-borne such as bluetongue, West Nile fever, vesicular stomatitis and New World screwworm. Changes in distribution will be partially modulated by El Niño Southern Oscillation events, which will become more frequent and lead to a greater frequency of droughts and floods. Active disease surveillance for animal diseases in South America, particularly for vector-borne diseases, is very poor. Disease reporting is often lacking, which affects knowledge of disease distribution and impact, and preparedness for early response. Improved reporting for animal diseases that may be affected by climate change is needed for better prevention and intervention measures in susceptible livestock, wildlife and vectors in South America. This requires contributions from multidisciplinary experts, including meteorologists, epidemiologists, biologists and ecologists, and from local communities.","Animal health; Biodiversity; Climate change; Conservation medicine; Ecosystem; Emerging disease; Forecasting; Risk; South America; Vector-borne disease","animal; animal disease; article; biodiversity; climate; communicable disease; disaster; disease carrier; ecosystem; forecasting; greenhouse effect; health survey; mandatory reporting; risk assessment; South America; Animal Diseases; Animals; Biodiversity; Climate; Communicable Diseases, Emerging; Disease Vectors; Ecosystem; Forecasting; Greenhouse Effect; Mandatory Reporting; Natural Disasters; Risk Assessment; Sentinel Surveillance; South America; Animalia; Ovis aries",,,,,,"Aguirre, A.A., Ostfeld, R.S., Tabor, G.M., House, C., Pearl, M.C., (2002) Conservation medicine: Ecological health in practice, , Oxford University Press, New York; Anyamba, A., Chretien, J.P., Small, J., Compton, T., Linthicum, K., Developing climate anomalies suggest potential risks for 2006-2007 (2006) Int. J. Hlth Geogr, 5. , http://www.ij-healthgeographics.com/content/5/1/60, 60 pp. Available at; Baylis, M., Githek